<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>UsuRpeR</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Member<br />
	
	
	<br />
	Joined: Sep 2002<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Although guild raids are important, especially contested mobs, I feel once an LDoN adventure is started, one has made a commitment to finish it and as a courtesy to your fellow gamers, guildies or not, one is obligated to finish.<br />
<br />
For any guildie, raids take priority over everything else. LDoN I think is the exception.  If you're playing on a specified raid night, you should leave plenty of time to ensure you are present for a raid if you are adventuring.  If you take an adventure close to raid time you are doing not only your guild a disservice, but your fellow players as well. <br />
<br />
Once you got the adventure, at the least you should have spoken up, informed your fellow players you both had a raid in 30 minutes, and given the group the option to continue knowing you would leave, or allowing them to cancel and reform before getting into the dungeon.<br />
<br />
On a side note, guilds as a whole also need to be considerate of this "unwritten rule" of commitment to LDoN adventures.  On specified raid nights, one is on and playing, there is no excuse not to be at the raid early and ready to go. However, if an unscheduled raid is called, no guild should penalize their members in anyway if they are involved in an adventure. Once the adventure is over, the members would then head immediately to the raid.<br />
<br />
If you're in a heavy raiding guild where LDoN adventures are not acceptable for being late or not showing to raids, then you should stick to all guildie adventures only so fellow gamers don't get screwed.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br /><img src="http://www.clan-forsaken.com/usurper/rangerepics.gif" border="0" alt=""><br />
