	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Legran</b><br /><i>Roughly<br />
1 hour BoT = 1AA<br />
1 hour ldon = 50%AA and 50 adventure points.<br />
<br />
to me 1 hour = 1 hour.  If you waste an hour in a pick up exp group or you waste an hour ditching an LDoN they are equally bad.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Maybe this will explain it to you.  Let's say you join an xp group and stay a half hour and then have to bug out.  Using the above rates you have stated, that group would have earned 50% AA during that half hour you were with them.  When you leave they may or may not waste any time replacing you, they may or not even keep playing at all.  They may log into real life to enjoy time with their kids or wife or even sleep.  The point is that they spent 1/2 hour of their time and they got the experience that they earned during that time.<br />
<br />
On the other hand lets say that you are in an LDoN adventure that is taking an hour to beat and you leave after 30 minutes and that makes it highly unlikely if not impossible for the group to win the adventure.  So they have invested 1/2 hour to get (once again using the above expected return) 25% AA and 25 LDoN points.  However, since they can't win without your participation they only get 25% AA and get ripped off for the 25 LDoN points because you bailed.  Even if they replaced you right away it would mean starting up another adventure and not getting those 25 points.  You didn't tell them you might bail if your guild calls a raid.  They haven't agreed to that scenario but you have forced it on them.<br />
<br />
That's what is wrong.<br />
<br />
It comes down to responsibilites and living up to them.  Plenty of people in the world today don't believe in that.<br />
<br />
And before anybody gives me grief over it, yeah I know it is a hypothetical situation and it has holes in it but it isn't too far off from the originally described scenario.  But if the member leaving is required for the group to succeed then it is pretty accurate.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Legran</b><br /><i>But I think the lesson to me from this is clear .. stay the hell away from LDoN adventures ... LDoNers take this stuff way more seriously than I do :P.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Yes, if you are going to bug out of any LDoN adventure regardless of what it does to the people in the group anytime something in game comes up that you would rather do then you are right.  Stay away from LDoN adventures.  Especially if your's and your Guild's reputations are important.<br />
<br />
And to all you people with the eloquence to say "guild > all," that is fine if that is the way you want to behave but then take some of the previous posters fine advice and stay out of LDoN when there is any chance you will be called away or at the very least make it a point to inform any group you join that if your guild calls a raid you will be leaving whether or not the adventure is over.  To do any less would be fraud.</p>
	
	
	
