<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Riudi Oaknoggin</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Senior Member<br />
	
	
	<br />
	Joined: Sep 2000<br />
	Location: Wanderer
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>My deal is...<br />
<br />
The commitment thing.  Why is an LDoN more important than an exp group?  Because once you start one, you are committed to finish or one of two things happen -<br />
<br />
- The group will win without you<br />
<br />
- The group will lose without you.<br />
<br />
The overriding concern here from many people is that if you leave, the group has a better chance of losing than if you were to stay.  This is why it is more important for you to hang around till the bitter end.  People are depending on you to fulfill your part of that adventure until it is over.  A number of cliche's come to mind - When the going gets tough the tough get going, no I in Team (even though there's a me).<br />
<br />
It sounds silly to place so much importance on what boils down to a video game.  After all, no one is harmed by you leaving the adventure early, right?  It really boils down to your own character, and personal feelings.  For many of the people in raiding guilds, they will drop anything to be there when a raid is called.  For others, they will finish what they started because that is important to them.  It is a character issue, not just a game issue.<br />
<br />
As far as how I treat LDoN's, our guild raids' from 5 PM till 9 to 11 PM.  Everyone doing LDoN's are expected to be finished by 5 PM, and no one is to start an LDoN or join one at least 30 minutes before a called raid.  This way we don't have to worry about if we're going to get it done or not.  If a raid is called on the spur of the moment, our people in LDoN's are not required to be at the raid until that LDoN is done.  They are encouraged to hurry the hell up...  <img src="images/smilies/biggrin.gif" border="0" alt="" title="big grin" smilieid="4" /> <br />
<br />
Doing an LDoN is a commitment.  Not a binding one, to be sure, but a commitment anyway.  If you know that you're going to have a raid soon, or the might be a raid soon, then you should forget the LDoN and go for reg. exp.  It sounds like you would rather do that anyway.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />It comes down to responsibilites and living up to them. Plenty of people in the world today don't believe in that.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I'll agree with this 100%.  It's about character.  A guild can win a raid without you.  It's not as easy to do with an adventure.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br />Riudi Oaknoggin<br />
The Redneck Ranger<br />
Bertoxx<br />
<br />
"He who laughs last, thinks fastest."<br />
                      -  <i>When the Devil Dances</i>  -  By John Ringo<br />
